<br>
First of all, let's examine what a newton and a kilogram are.<br>
<br>
A newton is a unit of force, the amount of force needed to accelerate a 1 kilogram substance 1 m/s^2. In the presence of earth's gravity, one can also use it to measure weight.<br>
<br>
A kilogram a unit of mass. Note that mass is not equal to weight. Objects have mass if they are in space, and if they are upon the earth, or whereever else they may be. Objects only have weight if they are upon a celestrial object, ei, Earth, Moon, Mars, etc.<br>
<br>
On the earth, aproximently 10 neutons is equal to 1 kilogram of mass. This is because the earth exerts a constant pull of 9.8 m/s^2 upon any object near the surface of the earth. Because a=F/m, and in this case, m=1 kg and a=9.8 m/s^2, then the F=9.8 N. However, this only applies upon earth.<br>
<br>
