34399.4 nanotesla according to this site<br>
and the IGRF Model.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/space/model/magnetos/tsygan.html">nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/space...sygan.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
I'm going to simplify the calculations that are coming up by rounding to 34400nT = 0.0000344T<br>
If you wanted to use this field to produce lift only by passing a massive current through an object, The lorentz force F = IlB would probably be most useful.<br>
Force = Current(amps) * length of wire(meters) * magnetic field flux (in tesla).  The force is perpendicular to the field lines and the current flow.  The force is exerted on the body that has current flowing through it.  So at the equator where field lines are north-south, you'd have to run a current through a wire in an east-west orientation.<br>
<br>
The magnetic field drops off close to linearly for the first 1000 KM, with a slope of about .06nT/m.<br>
<br>
If you wanted to provide a force of (say) 2000N, enough to lift a person in a space suit, and you wanted them to hang onto a 1M long beam that would have the current passed through it, you'd have to pass about 58 million amps through it for the full duration of the acceleration.  I cant think of any less-efficient way to get into outer space.  <br>
<br>
This is actually the same principle employed by railguns.  In a railgun, you would use a magnet(something approaching 1 T, hopefully) and run a few thousand amps through the projectile as it travels the length of the barrel.  The US navy was experimenting with them to a certain extent, I believe.   A 1T field, btw, is HUGE.  most of the time, field is measured in gauss, which is 1T=10000gauss.   Refrigerator magnets are about 500-800g.  you can get commercial magnets that are about 8,000 gauss.  If you want significantly more field than that, you'll have to start looking at electromagnets.<br>
